<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-130-030 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 990 636</DOCID><JOURNAL>Software Magazine  June 15 1991 v11 n8 p40(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Sentry Publishing Company Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>13: Ashton-Tate Corporation. (one of 50 articles on top 50independent software companies)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Ashton-Tate (Rating).andO;Ticker:    TATE.andO;Topic:     Software PublishersRevenueSalesWorld MarketRatings.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>&quot;1990 was a pivotal year for us,&quot; said William P. Lyons, president and CEO ofstruggling Ashton-Tate Corp. Lyons noted that the firm shipped Version 1.1 ofthe flagship dBase IV product last July 31, while adding binary-compatibleversions of the DBMS for computers made by DEC, Sun and Apple.andM;After surviving a difficult first half of 1990, Ashton-Tate reported a profitin the third quarter.andP;  Nonetheless, the company remained deeply in the redfor calendar 1990 with revenues totaling $230.5 million, down from $265.3million.andM;Other products introduced in 1990 include the Applause II presentationgraphics software, the Control Room package for inspecting computerconfigurations, the low-end Framework XE decision support software andupdates of FullWrite Professional and FullImpact for the Macintosh.andM;In addition, Ashton-Tate in 1990 appealed a ruling made in its copyrightinfringement lawsuit against Fox Software, Inc., in which a U.S.andP;  DistrictCourt ruled that the copyrights of its dBase line of products were invalid.andO;That ruling was rescinded in April 1991.andM;&quot;With the new copyright decision, we believe our profitability willaccelerate,&quot; said Lyons.andM;&quot;Database management software is going to become more important in the 1990s.andO;We expect to continue our leadership in this decade,&quot; he said.andO;</TEXT></DOC>